Data source

# Loading data:

spotify_data_top <- 
  read_csv("data/ATop 1990-2022.csv")

spotify_streams <- 
  read_csv("data/spotify_streams.csv")

The spotify_data_top dataset I am using collected Spotify-made playlists that include between 50-130 tracks of the most popular songs each year from 1990-2022. There is information on each songâs artist, album release date, genre, and other characteristics (i.e.Â BPM, key, and time signature). This data was taken from Kaggle, courtesy of user KRISTOFFER.

The spotify_streams dataset I am using collected data on 10000 Spotify songs and information on their number of streams. This data was taken from Kaggle, courtesy of user RAKKESH ARAVIND G.

I anticipate joining these data sets together and one way I could match them would be through the song name and artist name variables, which are listed differently in each dataset. Thus, I would have to rename these columns later so that they are consistent.

Why this data

I chose to use these datasets because I think it would be interesting to look at the songs that were considered âpopularâ throughout the years form 1990-2022. The spotify_data_top has a lot of comprehensive information on the musical elements of each individual song (e.g.Â dancebility, genres, time signature, and key), and I think it could be useful to analyze if there are any correlations among these elements and âpopularityâ. The spotify_streams dataset provides a more concrete, quantitative measure of âpopularityâ through collecting the number of streams (or how many times the song is played on the platform) for each song. Thus, I think it would be helpful to merge these two datasets together to look at the number of streams as an indicator of popularity.

The datasets seem to be sufficiently complex. spotify_data_top has 2610 observations and 26 variables. There are 12 categorical, 12 numeric, and 2 date and time-related variables. spotify_streams has 11084 rows and 9 variables. There are 3 categorical and 6 numeric variables.

Potential data issues

One potential issue Iâm going to face in terms of merging is having to remove/ work around missing values. Since Iâm thinking of merging by song and artist name, it will be a bit hard since a couple of song names in the spotify_streams dataset is missing. Another challenge I will face will be regarding the date and time variables in the spotify_data_top dataset. I might have to mutate these rows so that it shows the year, month, day separately. I may also need to find a better way to represent time numerically. I also need to rename a lot of the columns because the variable names are not quite clear as to what theyâre representing. For example, the time variable actually represents the length of the song in minutes and seconds. Another issue that that the spotify_data_top dataset does not have any information on songs from 2021, 1 which will impact my analysis going forward if I decide to look at songs across time. Overall, the datasets seem relatively clean.
